<paragraph id="FBA0A2A76938832749433296921A935E" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="03DB7C0F047F9BF4149FD7684E6CD5A7" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">China (Yunnan).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C347D4FE9A4CFF090CF0D028ACE7BB7F" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="EE3C985A1FAE344E53BC082F4C986434" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="30C44B9C1EB56375E292E33149624A5D" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
Specific name from Latin, 
<taxonomicName id="693873AB33F92D2C1FB540D616AA6BF8" authorityName="Zhang &amp; Kang" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Ptychopteridae" genus="Ptychoptera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ptychoptera cordata" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordata">
<emphasis id="CCA1662B6906E81D8F00D6544A92C4DB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Ptychoptera cordata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(adjective, feminine, meaning 
<normalizedToken id="3161CAD2DD11763CFA941CED97C7D7EC" originalValue="“cordate”">&quot;cordate&quot;</normalizedToken>
), referring to the postnotum with a cordiform spot.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="67C671FC74A610203232C05DD08D3B90" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="2DD8FD8AF5DBEDB04C59CDC2417681E6" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1A95689FED552A190D5F0E75398BF515" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="20F965AFEF46395F6CD7D93C3921474D" genus="P." lsidName="P. formosensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="formosensis">
<emphasis id="54D77B183882F799FDB4F3A3DA20D9B4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">P. formosensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from China and Japan but can be separated from the latter by the postnotum dark brown with a cordiform yellow spot, the apical stylus of the gonostylus finger-shaped, and the apical process of paramere semilunar with apex expanding outward. In 
<taxonomicName id="68F0AF75A13F02F4CC981E96407BCFAD" genus="P." lsidName="P. formosensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="formosensis">
<emphasis id="52389688979FAA2AF4D22676B3DBE35B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">P. formosensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the postnotum is uniformly black, the apical stylus of the gonostylus is flat tongue-like, and the apical process of the paramere is bilobed (
<bibRefCitation id="09366760FC5DF14EC78C6F6762CF48FA" DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zoosymposia.3.1.23" author="Nakamura, T" journalOrPublisher="Zoosymposia" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" pagination="273 - 303" refId="B15" refString="Nakamura, T, Saigusa, T, 2009. Taxonomic study of the family Ptychopteridae of Japan (Diptera). Zoosymposia 3: 273 - 303, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zoosymposia.3.1.23" title="Taxonomic study of the family Ptychopteridae of Japan (Diptera)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zoosymposia.3.1.23" volume="3" year="2009">Nakamura and Saigusa 2009</bibRefCitation>
). This new species is also similar to 
<taxonomicName id="65BDF5A161A1F15CC23CEF5976B61E08" genus="P." lsidName="P. annandalei" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="annandalei">
<emphasis id="ADBB2C6940FF3FB0C991537FEBF2B5F9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">P. annandalei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Brunetti, 1918 from Burma, but can be separated from the latter by the apical process of paramere semilunar with apex expanding outward, the apical stylus of the gonostylus and the secondary lobe of the apical stylus of the gonostylus finger-shaped, not crossing. In 
<taxonomicName id="70E3F05547494AEEEBCB4BA8E45278DA" genus="P." lsidName="P. annandalei" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="annandalei">
<emphasis id="C418AC7CD9A9351332C8990D78C7C9C3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">P. annandalei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the apical lobes of the paramere are dorsoventrally flattened and semicircular with the spine curved anteriorly, apices of the apical stylus and secondary lobe of the gonostylus are crossing (
<bibRefCitation id="61C1B3602AB6DF45BB9E13D8D3ED127E" author="Fasbender, A" journalOrPublisher="PhD Dissertation, Iowa State University, Ames" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B8" refString="Fasbender, A, 2014. Phylogeny and diversity of the phantom crane flies (Diptera: Ptychopteridae). PhD Dissertation, Iowa State University, Ames" title="Phylogeny and diversity of the phantom crane flies (Diptera: Ptychopteridae)." year="2014">Fasbender 2014</bibRefCitation>
). This new species is also similar to 
<taxonomicName id="9521EAFAD64C9E954D3333975CA351AC" genus="P." lsidName="P. perbona" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="perbona">
<emphasis id="5FFD56115BC7B920F911CFB733DD669A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">P. perbona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Alexander, 1946 from Burma, but can be separated from the latter by the mediotergite with a cordiform yellow spot, the apical stylus of the gonostylus finger-shaped, the apex of the terminal division of the hypandrium with an umbelliform lobe. In 
<taxonomicName id="731100F6693A9C0B461B2D090CC3ED22" genus="P." lsidName="P. perbona" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="perbona">
<emphasis id="159A215E0704B913ECBF9C11D1300C04" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">P. perbona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the mediotergite is uniformly black, the apical stylus of the gonostylus is stylate, the apex of the terminal division of the hypandrium has a pair of needle-like lateral lobes (
<bibRefCitation id="C5AB8C9A41D8D4CBF3C57BC7992D3519" author="Alexander, CP" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B5" refString="Alexander, CP, 1946. Entomological results from the Swedish expedition 1934 to Burma and British India. Diptera: Ptychopteridae. Collected by Rene Malaise. Arkiv for Zoologi 38A(2): 1-10." title="Entomological results from the Swedish expedition 1934 to Burma and British India. Diptera: Ptychopteridae. Collected by Rene Malaise. Arkiv for Zoologi 38 A (2): 1 - 10." year="1946">Alexander 1946</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="4A97915256293C8DDF9DABD067C4CE29" author="Fasbender, A" journalOrPublisher="PhD Dissertation, Iowa State University, Ames" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" refId="B8" refString="Fasbender, A, 2014. Phylogeny and diversity of the phantom crane flies (Diptera: Ptychopteridae). PhD Dissertation, Iowa State University, Ames" title="Phylogeny and diversity of the phantom crane flies (Diptera: Ptychopteridae)." year="2014">Fasbender 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
